🧠 Tradable – Mobile MVP Rules (React Native Version)

You are working on a production-bound MVP called “Tradable”.

GLOBAL RULES

Do NOT introduce new frameworks, databases, or services unless explicitly asked.

Do NOT refactor working code unless necessary for the requested task.

Do NOT remove existing functionality without explaining why and getting confirmation.

Keep scope minimal: build only what is required to support real users.

Prefer clarity and correctness over clever abstractions.

TECH STACK (LOCKED)

React Native (Expo Dev Client) + TypeScript

Node.js backend (Express/Fastify)

Supabase (Postgres + Auth)

LiveKit for video

NativeWind or StyleSheet (NO Tailwind web tooling)

Zod for validation

ARCHITECTURE RULES

All secrets must stay on the backend server.

Supabase service role keys must NEVER exist in the mobile app.

LiveKit tokens must be generated ONLY on the backend.

Database writes must go through authenticated backend routes.

The mobile app must never directly use the Supabase service role key.

Request lifecycle statuses are strictly:

open → matched → in_call → completed OR canceled


Do not invent new statuses without approval.

CODE STYLE

Strong typing everywhere (no any unless unavoidable).

Backend logic lives in /backend.

Mobile app logic lives in /tradable.

No database access directly inside mobile components.

Shared utilities go in /lib.

MOBILE APP RULES

Use functional components only.

No server-only logic inside the app.

Environment variables must use EXPO_PUBLIC_ prefix if client-safe.

Never expose secrets via environment variables.

Handle loading and error states explicitly.

Keep UI simple and functional — no animations unless requested.

Ensure accessibility: labels, touch targets, readable text.

LIVEKIT RULES

Room names must be deterministic (e.g., requestId).

Only the customer who created the request and the pro who claimed it may join.

Token generation must verify identity before issuing access.

Always clean up call state on leave/end.

DELIVERABLE DISCIPLINE

When creating new files, explain briefly why they exist.

When changing existing files, explain what changed and why.

Prefer small, incremental changes over large rewrites.

Never scaffold unnecessary architecture.

DEVELOPMENT MODE RULES

Use Expo Dev Client (NOT Expo Go).

Native modules must be properly installed before usage.

Do not suggest web-only packages (e.g., react-dom).

Do not suggest Next.js or App Router patterns.

This is a mobile app, not a web app.